  "market_context": "Price in an uptrend making consecutive higher highs; RSI indicator below 70, showing weakening momentum despite rising price.",
  "key_observation": "Price printed a higher high while the RSI simultaneously printed a lower high, forming a classic bearish divergence indicating loss of upward momentum.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: The analyst identified two successive swing highs on the price chart (upper panel).",
    "Step 2: The analyst switched attention to the RSI indicator (lower panel) and observed that the second RSI high was lower than the first, despite price making a higher high.",
    "Step 3: The analyst confirmed the bearish divergence by drawing connecting lines between the price highs and RSI highs, visually highlighting the opposing directions.",
    "Step 4: The analyst noted the subsequent strong downward price movement after the divergence formed, confirming its validity as a reversal signal."
  ],
  "outcome": "Strong bearish reversal occurred immediately after the divergence was identified, with price dropping sharply.",
  "lessons": "Bearish divergence requires comparing price highs with indicator highs only; misidentifying lows instead of highs leads to false signals. Confirmation via price action (reversal move) increases reliability.",
